PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Incomplete Left Bundle Branch Block by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Incomplete Left Bundle Branch Block by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of a wide QRS complex with evidence of delayed conduction to the left ventricle, manifest as a widened initial portion of the QRS complex in leads V5, V6, I and aVL and with QRS duration less than 120 ms. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: Incomplete Left Bundle Branch Block by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of a wide QRS complex with evidence of delayed conduction to the left ventricle, manifest as a widened initial portion of the QRS complex in leads V5, V6, I and aVL and with QRS duration less than 120 ms. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Incomplete Right Bundle Branch Block by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Incomplete Right Bundle Branch Block by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of a wide QRS complex with evidence of delayed conduction to the right ventricle, manifested by a widened initial portion of the QRS in V1 and V2, a widened S wave in V5, V6, I and aVL, and with QRS duration less than 120 ms. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: Incomplete Right Bundle Branch Block by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of a wide QRS complex with evidence of delayed conduction to the right ventricle, manifested by a widened initial portion of the QRS in V1 and V2, a widened S wave in V5, V6, I and aVL, and with QRS duration less than 120 ms. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Inferior Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Inferior Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of pathologic Q waves in leads III, aVF and often II, which is suggestive of myocardial infarction of the inferior wall of the left ventricle. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: Inferior Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of pathologic Q waves in leads III, aVF and often II, which is suggestive of myocardial infarction of the inferior wall of the left ventricle. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Interchanged Limb Electrodes by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Interchanged Limb Electrodes by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic recording in which two or more of the limb electrodes are switched resulting in improper representation of the affected leads. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: Interchanged Limb Electrodes by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic recording in which two or more of the limb electrodes are switched resulting in improper representation of the affected leads. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Interchanged Precordial Electrodes by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Interchanged Precordial Electrodes by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic recording in which two or more of the precordial electrodes are switched resulting in improper representation of the affected leads. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: Interchanged Precordial Electrodes by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic recording in which two or more of the precordial electrodes are switched resulting in improper representation of the affected leads. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Interpolated Premature Ventricular Complex by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Interpolated Premature Ventricular Complex by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of a premature ventricular complex which occurs between two normal QRS complexes which have normal timing. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: Interpolated Premature Ventricular Complex by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of a premature ventricular complex which occurs between two normal QRS complexes which have normal timing. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Intra-Atrial Conduction Delay by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Intra-Atrial Conduction Delay by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of a delay in impulse propagation through the atria. This is characterized by broad P waves which are often biphasic in V1. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: Intra-Atrial Conduction Delay by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of a delay in impulse propagation through the atria. This is characterized by broad P waves which are often biphasic in V1. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Invalid ECG Waveforms

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Invalid ECG Waveforms
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic recording for which the displayed leads do not represent the individual's true ECG lead information. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: Invalid ECG Waveforms
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic recording for which the displayed leads do not represent the individual's true ECG lead information. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Isorhythmic Atrioventricular Dissociation

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Isorhythmic Atrioventricular Dissociation
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of a type of atrioventricular dissociation characterized by the atria (P waves) and ventricles (QRS complexes) beating at similar rates, although independently. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: Isorhythmic Atrioventricular Dissociation
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of a type of atrioventricular dissociation characterized by the atria (P waves) and ventricles (QRS complexes) beating at similar rates, although independently. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: J Point Elevation

ValueMeaning.preferredName: J Point Elevation
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of a significant elevation above the baseline of the J point. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: J Point Elevation
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of a significant elevation above the baseline of the J point. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Junctional Bradycardia by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Junctional Bradycardia by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of a junctional rhythm with a heat rate which is abnormally low. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: Junctional Bradycardia by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of a junctional rhythm with a heat rate which is abnormally low. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Junctional Escape Complexes by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Junctional Escape Complexes by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of an escape beat following a pause that originates at the AV junction; this manifests as a QRS complex of supraventricular origin not immediately preceded by a P wave. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: Junctional Escape Complexes by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of an escape beat following a pause that originates at the AV junction; this manifests as a QRS complex of supraventricular origin not immediately preceded by a P wave. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Junctional Escape Rhythm by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Junctional Escape Rhythm by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of a junctional rhythm that arises as a physiologic response to extreme slowing or arrest of sinus node activity. In this setting, a faster junctional rhythm may be a normal response to a very slow or absent sinus rate. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: Junctional Escape Rhythm by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of a junctional rhythm that arises as a physiologic response to extreme slowing or arrest of sinus node activity. In this setting, a faster junctional rhythm may be a normal response to a very slow or absent sinus rate. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Junctional Premature Complex by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Junctional Premature Complex by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of an ectopic impulse originating in the AV junction presenting as a QRS complex of supraventricular origin which is not preceded by a P wave. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: Junctional Premature Complex by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of an ectopic impulse originating in the AV junction presenting as a QRS complex of supraventricular origin which is not preceded by a P wave. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Junctional Rhythm by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Junctional Rhythm by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of a rhythm which originates in the AV junction and results in a normal heart rate. It is characterized by retrograde P waves which may be obscured by or may follow the QRS complexes. The QRS complexes may be narrow or may demonstrate aberration. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: Junctional Rhythm by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of a rhythm which originates in the AV junction and results in a normal heart rate. It is characterized by retrograde P waves which may be obscured by or may follow the QRS complexes. The QRS complexes may be narrow or may demonstrate aberration. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Junctional Tachycardia by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Junctional Tachycardia by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of a junctional rhythm with a heart rate which is abnormally elevated. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: Junctional Tachycardia by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of a junctional rhythm with a heart rate which is abnormally elevated. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Late R Wave Transition by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Late R Wave Transition by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding where the amplitude of the R wave does not become greater than the amplitude of the S wave until an unusually late point in the precordial leads, usually in leads V4 to V6. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: Late R Wave Transition by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding where the amplitude of the R wave does not become greater than the amplitude of the S wave until an unusually late point in the precordial leads, usually in leads V4 to V6. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Lateral Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Lateral Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of pathologic Q waves in leads V5, V6, I and aVL, which is suggestive of myocardial infarction of the lateral wall of the left ventricle. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: Lateral Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of pathologic Q waves in leads V5, V6, I and aVL, which is suggestive of myocardial infarction of the lateral wall of the left ventricle. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Left Anterior Fascicular Block by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Left Anterior Fascicular Block by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of a slightly widened QRS duration (typically less than 120 ms) with leftward frontal plane QRS axis and typically small Q waves in leads I and aVL. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: Left Anterior Fascicular Block by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of a slightly widened QRS duration (typically less than 120 ms) with leftward frontal plane QRS axis and typically small Q waves in leads I and aVL. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Left Bundle Branch Block by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Left Bundle Branch Block by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of a wide QRS complex with evidence of delayed conduction to the left ventricle, manifest as a widened initial portion of the QRS complex in leads V5, V6, I and aVL and with QRS duration greater than or equal to 120 ms.

Concepts.longName: Left Bundle Branch Block by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of a wide QRS complex with evidence of delayed conduction to the left ventricle, manifested as a widened initial portion of the QRS complex in leads V5, V6, I and aVL and with QRS duration greater than or equal to 120 ms. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Left Posterior Fascicular Block by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Left Posterior Fascicular Block by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of an S1Q3 pattern and QRS axis greater than or equal to 120 degrees. It is usually seen in association with other abnormalities (e.g. RBBB or RVH). (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: Left Posterior Fascicular Block by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of an S1Q3 pattern and QRS axis greater than or equal to 120 degrees. It is usually seen in association with other abnormalities (e.g. RBBB or RVH). (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Left Ventricular Conduction Delay by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Left Ventricular Conduction Delay by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding in which there is evidence that electrical transmission through the left ventricle is impaired. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: Left Ventricular Conduction Delay by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding in which there is evidence that electrical transmission through the left ventricle is impaired. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Left Ventricular Hypertrophy by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Left Ventricular Hypertrophy by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding suggestive of a hypertrophied left ventricle, characterized by large QRS amplitudes and secondary findings of left atrial enlargement, left axis deviation, or typical pattern of ST depression and T wave inversion. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: Left Ventricular Hypertrophy by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding suggestive of a hypertrophied left ventricle, characterized by large QRS amplitudes and secondary findings of left atrial enlargement, left axis deviation, or typical pattern of ST depression and T wave inversion. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Left Ventricular Hypertrophy with Strain by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Left Ventricular Hypertrophy with Strain by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding suggestive of a hypertrophied left ventricle, characterized by large QRS amplitudes, ST depression and T wave inversion. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: Left Ventricular Hypertrophy with Strain by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding suggestive of a hypertrophied left ventricle, characterized by large QRS amplitudes, ST depression and T wave inversion. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Low Amplitude QRS Complex by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Low Amplitude QRS Complex by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic recording showing smaller than usual QRS complexes in one or more leads. This may represent a technical issue with the ECG acquisition or characteristics of the individual. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: Low Amplitude QRS Complex by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic recording showing smaller than usual QRS complexes in one or more leads. This may represent a technical issue with the ECG acquisition or characteristics of the individual. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Low QRS Voltage by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Low QRS Voltage by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of a QRS amplitude less than or equal to 0.5 mV in the limb leads or QRS amplitude less than or equal to 1 mV in the precordial leads. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: Low QRS Voltage by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of a QRS amplitude less than or equal to 0.5 mV in the limb leads or QRS amplitude less than or equal to 1 mV in the precordial leads. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Marked Sinus Bradycardia by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Marked Sinus Bradycardia by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic tracing demonstrating sinus bradycardia, with a heart rate lower than an acceptable, predetermined threshold.  Different thresholds, for rate and/or duration, may apply to different patient populations.

Concepts.longName: Marked Sinus Bradycardia by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic tracing demonstrating sinus bradycardia, with a heart rate lower than an acceptable, predetermined threshold.  Different thresholds, for rate and/or duration, may apply to different patient populations.

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Multifocal Atrial Premature Complex by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Multifocal Atrial Premature Complex by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of premature atrial complexes which have 2 or more distinct morphologies, suggesting origin at more than one atrial site. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: Multifocal Atrial Premature Complex by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of premature atrial complexes which have 2 or more distinct morphologies, suggesting origin at more than one atrial site. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Multifocal Atrial Tachycardia by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Multifocal Atrial Tachycardia by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of a supraventricular arrhythmia characterized by 3 or more distinct P wave morphologies with an isoelectric baseline, variable PR intervals and no predominant atrial rhythm. The ventricular rate is typically 100-150 beats per minute. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: Multifocal Atrial Tachycardia by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of a supraventricular arrhythmia characterized by 3 or more distinct P wave morphologies with an isoelectric baseline, variable PR intervals and no predominant atrial rhythm. The ventricular rate is typically 100-150 beats per minute. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Multifocal Ventricular Premature Complex by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Multifocal Ventricular Premature Complex by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of premature ventricular complexes which have two or more distinct morphologies, suggesting origin at more than one ventricular site. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: Multifocal Ventricular Premature Complex by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of premature ventricular complexes which have two or more distinct morphologies, suggesting origin at more than one ventricular site. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Muscle Tremor Artifact

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Muscle Tremor Artifact
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic recording with intermittent mid to high frequency artifact in one or more leads due to muscular tremor or movement rather than cardiac activity. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: Muscle Tremor Artifact
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic recording with intermittent mid to high frequency artifact in one or more leads due to muscular tremor or movement rather than cardiac activity. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of pathologic Q waves, which is suggestive of myocardial infarction of one or more regions of the heart. No specification is provided for localization. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of pathologic Q waves, which is suggestive of myocardial infarction of one or more regions of the heart. No specification is provided for localization. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: New Anterior Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: New Anterior Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of pathologic Q waves in leads V3 and V4, which is suggestive of myocardial infarction of the anterior wall of the left ventricle and which is new compared to prior ECGs. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: New Anterior Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of pathologic Q waves in leads V3 and V4, which is suggestive of myocardial infarction of the anterior wall of the left ventricle and which is new compared to prior ECGs. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: New Anterolateral Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: New Anterolateral Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of pathologic Q waves in leads V3 through V6, which is suggestive of myocardial infarction of the anterolateral wall of the left ventricle and which is new compared to prior ECGs. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: New Anterolateral Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of pathologic Q waves in leads V3 through V6, which is suggestive of myocardial infarction of the anterolateral wall of the left ventricle and which is new compared to prior ECGs. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: New Anteroseptal Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: New Anteroseptal Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of pathologic Q waves in leads V1 through V4, which is suggestive of myocardial infarction of the anteroseptal wall of the left ventricle and which is new compared to prior ECGs. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: New Anteroseptal Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of pathologic Q waves in leads V1 through V4, which is suggestive of myocardial infarction of the anteroseptal wall of the left ventricle and which is new compared to prior ECGs. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.value: NEW EXTENSIVE ANTERIOR WALL MYOCARDIAL INFARCTION
PermissibleValues.valueDescription: New Extensive Anterior Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: New Extensive Anterior Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of pathologic Q waves in leads V1 to V6, I and aVL, which is suggestive of myocardial infarction involving the anterior and anterolateral walls of the left ventricle and which is new compared to prior ECGs. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: New Extensive Anterior Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of pathologic Q waves in leads V1 to V6, I and aVL, which is suggestive of myocardial infarction involving the anterior and anterolateral walls of the left ventricle and which is new compared to prior ECGs. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.value: NEW HIGH LATERAL WALL MYOCARDIAL INFARCTION
PermissibleValues.valueDescription: New High Lateral Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: New High Lateral Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of pathologic Q waves in leads I and aVL, which is suggestive of myocardial infarction of the high lateral wall of the left ventricle and which is new compared to prior ECGs. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: New High Lateral Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of pathologic Q waves in leads I and aVL, which is suggestive of myocardial infarction of the high lateral wall of the left ventricle and which is new compared to prior ECGs. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: New Inferior Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: New Inferior Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of pathologic Q waves in leads III, aVF and often II, which is suggestive of myocardial infarction of the inferior wall of the left ventricle and which is new compared to prior ECGs. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: New Inferior Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of pathologic Q waves in leads III, aVF and often II, which is suggestive of myocardial infarction of the inferior wall of the left ventricle and which is new compared to prior ECGs. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: New Lateral Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: New Lateral Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of pathologic Q waves in leads V5, V6, I and aVL, which is suggestive of myocardial infarction of the lateral wall of the left ventricle and which is new compared to prior ECGs. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: New Lateral Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of pathologic Q waves in leads V5, V6, I and aVL, which is suggestive of myocardial infarction of the lateral wall of the left ventricle and which is new compared to prior ECGs. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: New Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: New Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of pathologic Q waves, which is suggestive of myocardial infarction of one or more regions of the heart and which is new compared to prior ECGs. No specification is provided for localization. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: New Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of pathologic Q waves, which is suggestive of myocardial infarction of one or more regions of the heart and which is new compared to prior ECGs. No specification is provided for localization. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: New Posterior Wall Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: New Posterior Wall Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding in leads V1 or V2 of an initial R wave duration greater than or equal to 40 ms, R wave greater than S wave, and upright T wave, which is suggestive of myocardial infarction of the posterior wall of the left ventricle, and which is new compared to prior ECGs. Evidence of inferior or lateral myocardial infarction is usually also present. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: New Posterior Wall Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding in leads V1 or V2 of an initial R wave duration greater than or equal to 40 ms, R wave greater than S wave, and upright T wave, which is suggestive of myocardial infarction of the posterior wall of the left ventricle, and which is new compared to prior ECGs. Evidence of inferior or lateral myocardial infarction is usually also present. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: New Septal Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: New Septal Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of pathologic Q waves in leads V1, V2 and often V3, which is suggestive of myocardial infarction of the intraventricular septum and which is new compared to prior ECGs. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: New Septal Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of pathologic Q waves in leads V1, V2 and often V3, which is suggestive of myocardial infarction of the intraventricular septum and which is new compared to prior ECGs. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Non Q Wave Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Non Q Wave Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of ST and T wave abnormalities in the absence of pathologic Q waves, which is suggestive of myocardial infarction in one or more regions of the heart. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: Non Q Wave Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of ST and T wave abnormalities in the absence of pathologic Q waves, which is suggestive of myocardial infarction in one or more regions of the heart. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.value: NONCONDUCTED P WAVE PHYSIOLOGY NOT DEFINED
PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Nonconducted P Wave Physiology Not Defined by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Nonconducted P Wave Physiology Not Defined by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of a P wave that either does not conduct to the ventricle or that does not result in ventricular activation.

Concepts.longName: Nonconducted P Wave Physiology Not Defined by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of a P wave that either does not conduct to the ventricle or that does not result in ventricular activation.

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Nonsustained Supraventricular Tachycardia by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Nonsustained Supraventricular Tachycardia by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic tracing demonstrating supraventricular tachycardia of less than thirty seconds duration. Different thresholds, for rate and/or duration, may apply to different patient populations.

Concepts.longName: Nonsustained Supraventricular Tachycardia by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic tracing demonstrating supraventricular tachycardia of less than thirty seconds duration. Different thresholds, for rate and/or duration, may apply to different patient populations.

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Sinus rhythm

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Sinus rhythm
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of a cardiac rhythm that originates in the sinoatrial node and is considered normal for the population.

Concepts.longName: Normal Sinus Rhythm
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of an atrial rhythm which originates from the sinoatrial node that is considered normal for the population. There are no extra beats or conduction abnormalities. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.value: OLD OR AGE INDETERMINATE ANTEROLATERAL WALL MYOCARDIAL INFARCTION
PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Old or Age Indeterminate Anterolateral Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Old or Age Indeterminate Anterolateral Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of pathologic Q waves in leads V3 through V6, which is suggestive of myocardial infarction of the anterolateral wall of the left ventricle, without evidence of current or ongoing acute infarction. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: Old or Age Indeterminate Anterolateral Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of pathologic Q waves in leads V3 through V6, which is suggestive of myocardial infarction of the anterolateral wall of the left ventricle, without evidence of current or ongoing acute infarction. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.value: OLD OR AGE INDETERMINATE ANTEROSEPTAL WALL MYOCARDIAL INFARCTION
PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Old or Age Indeterminate Anteroseptal Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Old or Age Indeterminate Anteroseptal Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of pathologic Q waves in leads V1 through V4, which is suggestive of myocardial infarction of the anteroseptal wall of the left ventricle, without evidence of current or ongoing acute infarction. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: Old or Age Indeterminate Anteroseptal Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of pathologic Q waves in leads V1 through V4, which is suggestive of myocardial infarction of the anteroseptal wall of the left ventricle, without evidence of current or ongoing acute infarction. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.value: OLD OR AGE INDETERMINATE EXTENSIVE ANTERIOR WALL MYOCARDIAL INFARCTION
PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Old or Age Indeterminate Extensive Anterior Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Old or Age Indeterminate Extensive Anterior Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of pathologic Q waves in leads V1 to V6, I and aVL, which is suggestive of myocardial infarction involving the anterior and anterolateral walls of the left ventricle, without evidence of current or ongoing acute infarction. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: Old or Age Indeterminate Extensive Anterior Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of pathologic Q waves in leads V1 to V6, I and aVL, which is suggestive of myocardial infarction involving the anterior and anterolateral walls of the left ventricle, without evidence of current or ongoing acute infarction. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.value: OLD OR AGE INDETERMINATE HIGH LATERAL WALL MYOCARDIAL INFARCTION
PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Old or Age Indeterminate High Lateral Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Old or Age Indeterminate High Lateral Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of pathologic Q waves in leads I and aVL, which is suggestive of myocardial infarction of the high lateral wall of the left ventricle, without evidence of current or ongoing acute infarction. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: Old or Age Indeterminate High Lateral Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of pathologic Q waves in leads I and aVL, which is suggestive of myocardial infarction of the high lateral wall of the left ventricle, without evidence of current or ongoing acute infarction. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.value: OLD OR AGE INDETERMINATE INFERIOR WALL MYOCARDIAL INFARCTION
PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Old or Age Indeterminate Inferior Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Old or Age Indeterminate Inferior Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of pathologic Q waves in leads III, aVF and often II, which is suggestive of myocardial infarction of the inferior wall of the left ventricle, without evidence of current or ongoing acute infarction. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: Old or Age Indeterminate Inferior Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of pathologic Q waves in leads III, aVF and often II, which is suggestive of myocardial infarction of the inferior wall of the left ventricle, without evidence of current or ongoing acute infarction. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.value: OLD OR AGE INDETERMINATE LATERAL WALL MYOCARDIAL INFARCTION
PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Old or Age Indeterminate Lateral Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Old or Age Indeterminate Lateral Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of pathologic Q waves in leads V5, V6, I and aVL, which is suggestive of myocardial infarction of the lateral wall of the left ventricle, without evidence of current or ongoing acute infarction. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: Old or Age Indeterminate Lateral Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of pathologic Q waves in leads V5, V6, I and aVL, which is suggestive of myocardial infarction of the lateral wall of the left ventricle, without evidence of current or ongoing acute infarction. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.value: OLD OR AGE INDETERMINATE POSTERIOR WALL MYOCARDIAL INFARCTION
PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Old or Age Indeterminate Posterior Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Old or Age Indeterminate Posterior Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding in leads V1 or V2 of an initial R wave duration greater than or equal to 40 ms, R wave greater than S wave, and upright T wave, which is suggestive of myocardial infarction of the posterior wall of the left ventricle, without evidence of current or ongoing acute infarction. Evidence of inferior or lateral myocardial infarction is usually also present. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: Old or Age Indeterminate Posterior Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding in leads V1 or V2 of an initial R wave duration greater than or equal to 40 ms, R wave greater than S wave, and upright T wave, which is suggestive of myocardial infarction of the posterior wall of the left ventricle, without evidence of current or ongoing acute infarction. Evidence of inferior or lateral myocardial infarction is usually also present. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.value: OLD OR AGE UNDETERMINED RIGHT VENTRICULAR MYOCARDIAL INFARCTION
PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Old or Age Indeterminate Right Ventricular Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Old or Age Indeterminate Right Ventricular Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding, in the presence of an old or age indeterminate inferior wall myocardial infarction, of Q waves greater than or equal to 40 ms in duration in the right ventricular leads V4R through V6R. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: Old or Age Indeterminate Right Ventricular Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding, in the presence of an old or age indeterminate inferior wall myocardial infarction, of Q waves greater than or equal to 40 ms in duration in the right ventricular leads V4R through V6R. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.value: OLD OR AGE INDETERMINATE SEPTAL WALL MYOCARDIAL INFARCTION
PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Old or Age Indeterminate Septal Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Old or Age Indeterminate Septal Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of pathologic Q waves in leads V1, V2 and often V3, which is suggestive of myocardial infarction of the intraventricular septum, without evidence of current or ongoing acute infarction. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: Old or Age Indeterminate Septal Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of pathologic Q waves in leads V1, V2 and often V3, which is suggestive of myocardial infarction of the intraventricular septum, without evidence of current or ongoing acute infarction. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Other Incorrect Electrode Placement

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Other Incorrect Electrode Placement
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic recording in which one or more electrodes are incorrectly placed but further details are not provided. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: Other Incorrect Electrode Placement
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic recording in which one or more electrodes are incorrectly placed but further details are not provided. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: P Wave Abnormality by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: P Wave Abnormality by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding for the P wave that is atypical either for the shape, duration, amplitude, axis or polarity. Abnormality of the P wave signifies aberrant propagation of the electrical impulse through the atria.

Concepts.longName: P Wave Abnormality by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding for the P wave that is atypical either for the shape, duration, amplitude, axis or polarity. Abnormality of the P wave signifies aberrant propagation of the electrical impulse through the atria.

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: P Wave Notched by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: P Wave Notched by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of P waves with two peaks longer in duration than normal and amplitude greater than normal. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: P Wave Notched by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of P waves with two peaks longer in duration than normal and amplitude greater than normal. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: P-mitrale by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: P-mitrale by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding suggesting underlying hypertrophy or dilatation of the left atrium. Electrocardiographic criteria used for the diagnosis of left atrial abnormality may include a bifid p wave, a biphasic p wave and/or a p wave duration of greater than 0.12 seconds.

Concepts.longName: P-mitrale by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding suggesting underlying hypertrophy or dilatation of the left atrium. Electrocardiographic criteria used for the diagnosis of left atrial abnormality may include a bifid p wave, a biphasic p wave and/or a p wave duration of greater than 0.12 seconds.

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: P-pulmonale by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: P-pulmonale by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding suggesting underlying hypertrophy or dilatation of the right atrium. Electrocardiographic criteria used for the diagnosis of right atrial abnormality may include a peaked p wave greater than 2.5 millimeters in amplitude in the inferior leads.

Concepts.longName: P-pulmonale by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding suggesting underlying hypertrophy or dilatation of the right atrium. Electrocardiographic criteria used for the diagnosis of right atrial abnormality may include a peaked p wave greater than 2.5 millimeters in amplitude in the inferior leads.

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Paced Atrial And Ventricular Rhythm

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Paced Atrial And Ventricular Rhythm
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding in which both the atrial and ventricular rhythm are controlled by an electrical impulse from an artificial cardiac pacemaker. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: Paced Atrial And Ventricular Rhythm
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding in which both the atrial and ventricular rhythm are controlled by an electrical impulse from an artificial cardiac pacemaker. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Paced Atrial Rhythm

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Paced Atrial Rhythm
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding in which the atrial rhythm is controlled by an electrical impulse from an artificial cardiac pacemaker. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: Paced Atrial Rhythm
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding in which the atrial rhythm is controlled by an electrical impulse from an artificial cardiac pacemaker. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Paced Rhythm

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Paced Rhythm
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding that the cardiac rhythm is initiated by an electrical impulse from a mechanical cardiac pacemaker.

Concepts.longName: Paced Rhythm
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding in which the cardiac rhythm is controlled by an electrical impulse from an artificial cardiac pacemaker. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Paced Ventricular Rhythm

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Paced Ventricular Rhythm
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding in which the ventricular rhythm is controlled by an electrical impulse from an artificial cardiac pacemaker. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: Paced Ventricular Rhythm
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding in which the ventricular rhythm is controlled by an electrical impulse from an artificial cardiac pacemaker. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Paroxysmal Atrial Fibrillation by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Paroxysmal Atrial Fibrillation by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic tracing demonstrating intermittent atrial fibrillation in the presence of sinus rhythm, junctional rhythm, or an atrial paced rhythm.

Concepts.longName: Paroxysmal Atrial Fibrillation by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic tracing demonstrating intermittent atrial fibrillation in the presence of sinus rhythm, junctional rhythm, or an atrial paced rhythm.

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Paroxysmal Atrioventricular Block by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Paroxysmal Atrioventricular Block by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of the sudden onset of transient AV block, which is often associated with preexisting conduction disorders. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: Paroxysmal Atrioventricular Block by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of the sudden onset of transient AV block, which is often associated with preexisting conduction disorders. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Paroxysmal Ventricular Tachycardia by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Paroxysmal Ventricular Tachycardia by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An episodic form of ventricular tachycardia, with abrupt onset and termination.

Concepts.longName: Paroxysmal Ventricular Tachycardia by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An episodic form of ventricular tachycardia, with abrupt onset and termination.

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Pause by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Pause by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic recording that demonstrates an R-R interval that exceeds a predefined duration threshold, irrespective of the underlying rhythm.

Concepts.longName: Pause by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic recording that demonstrates an R-R interval that exceeds a predefined duration threshold, irrespective of the underlying rhythm.

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Pause Greater Than Three Seconds by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Pause Greater Than Three Seconds by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic recording that demonstrates an R-R interval that exceeds three seconds, irrespective of the underlying rhythm.

Concepts.longName: Pause Greater Than Three Seconds by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic recording that demonstrates an R-R interval that exceeds three seconds, irrespective of the underlying rhythm.

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Persistent Atrial Fibrillation by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Persistent Atrial Fibrillation by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic tracing demonstrating atrial fibrillation that is present during the entire recording.

Concepts.longName: Persistent Atrial Fibrillation by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic tracing demonstrating atrial fibrillation that is present during the entire recording.

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Poor Quality ECG

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Poor Quality ECG
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic recording that does not show proper quality for reasons that are not otherwise described. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: Poor Quality ECG
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic recording that does not show proper quality for reasons that are not otherwise described. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Poor R Wave Progression by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Poor R Wave Progression by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of a lack of progression of R wave height across precordial leads. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: Poor R Wave Progression by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of a lack of progression of R wave height across precordial leads. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Posterior Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Posterior Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding in leads V1 or V2 of an initial R wave duration greater than or equal to 40 ms, R wave greater than S wave, and upright T wave, which is suggestive of myocardial infarction of the posterior wall of the left ventricle. Evidence of inferior or lateral myocardial infarction is usually also present. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: Posterior Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding in leads V1 or V2 of an initial R wave duration greater than or equal to 40 ms, R wave greater than S wave, and upright T wave, which is suggestive of myocardial infarction of the posterior wall of the left ventricle. Evidence of inferior or lateral myocardial infarction is usually also present. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: PR Segment Depression by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: PR Segment Depression by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of PR segment depression below the iso-electric line in multiple precordial and/or limb leads. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: PR Segment Depression by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of PR segment depression below the iso-electric line in multiple precordial and/or limb leads. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Prolonged QT Interval

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Prolonged QT Interval
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A QT interval that is prolonged. The length of the QT interval varies with the heart rate.

Concepts.longName: Prolonged QT Interval by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding in which the QT interval not corrected for heart rate is prolonged. Thresholds for different age, gender, and patient populations exist. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Prolonged ST Segment by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Prolonged ST Segment by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of a prolonged ST segment, resulting in an increased QT interval, without lengthening of the T wave duration; this may be observed in hypocalcemia. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: Prolonged ST Segment by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of a prolonged ST segment, resulting in an increased QT interval, without lengthening of the T wave duration; this may be observed in hypocalcemia. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: QRS Axis Indeterminate

ValueMeaning.preferredName: QRS Axis Indeterminate
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding in which the frontal plane QRS axis cannot be calculated.

Concepts.longName: QRS Axis Indeterminate
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding in which the frontal plane QRS axis cannot be calculated.

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: QRS Complex Abnormality by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: QRS Complex Abnormality by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of a non-specific abnormality of the QRS complex, which is atypical in shape, duration, amplitude, axis or polarity. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: QRS Complex Abnormality by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of a non-specific abnormality of the QRS complex, which is atypical in shape, duration, amplitude, axis or polarity. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: QTcB Prolongation

ValueMeaning.preferredName: QTcB Prolongation
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding in which the QT interval corrected for heart rate using Bazett's formula is prolonged. Thresholds for different age, gender, and patient populations exist. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: QTcB Prolongation
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding in which the QT interval corrected for heart rate using Bazett's formula is prolonged. Thresholds for different age, gender, and patient populations exist. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: QTcB Shortened

ValueMeaning.preferredName: QTcB Shortened
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding in which the QT interval corrected for heart rate using Bazett's formula is shortened. Thresholds for different age, gender, and patient populations exist. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: QTcB Shortened
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding in which the QT interval corrected for heart rate using Bazett's formula is shortened. Thresholds for different age, gender, and patient populations exist. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: QTcF Prolongation

ValueMeaning.preferredName: QTcF Prolongation
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding in which the QT interval corrected for heart rate using Fridericia's formula is prolonged. Thresholds for different age, gender, and patient populations exist.

Concepts.longName: QTcF Prolongation
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding in which the QT interval corrected for heart rate using Fridericia's formula is prolonged. Thresholds for different age, gender, and patient populations exist.

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: QTcF Shortened

ValueMeaning.preferredName: QTcF Shortened
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding in which the QT interval corrected for heart rate using Fridericia's formula is shortened. Thresholds for different age, gender, and patient populations exist. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: QTcF Shortened
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding in which the QT interval corrected for heart rate using Fridericia's formula is shortened. Thresholds for different age, gender, and patient populations exist. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Quality Problem Not Otherwise Specified by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Quality Problem Not Otherwise Specified by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic artifact or recording error with unknown origin or which is not described otherwise. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: Quality Problem Not Otherwise Specified by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic artifact or recording error with unknown origin or which is not described otherwise. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: R On T Phenomenon by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: R On T Phenomenon by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The occurrence of a premature ventricular complex near the peak of the T wave in electrocardiography; it may lead to ventricular tachycardia or fibrillation.

Concepts.longName: R On T Phenomenon by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding in which the R wave of a premature ventricular complex occurs on top of the T wave of the preceding beat. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: R Wave Notched by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: R Wave Notched by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of an R wave variant in which there is a small deflection of the R wave, with changing polarity, within the QRS complex.

Concepts.longName: R Wave Notched by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of an R wave variant in which there is a small deflection of the R wave, with changing polarity, within the QRS complex.

PermissibleValues.value: REPOLARIZATION ABNORMALITY SECONDARY TO VENTRICULAR HYPERTROPHY
PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Repolarization Abnormality Secondary To Ventricular Hypertrophy

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Repolarization Abnormality Secondary To Ventricular Hypertrophy
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of ST depression and T wave inversion in the presence of increased QRS amplitude which are thought to be due to left ventricular hypertrophy.

Concepts.longName: Repolarization Abnormality Secondary To Ventricular Hypertrophy
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of ST depression and T wave inversion in the presence of increased QRS amplitude which are thought to be due to left ventricular hypertrophy.

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Right Bundle Branch Block by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Right Bundle Branch Block by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of a wide QRS complex with evidence of delayed conduction to the right ventricle, manifested by a widened initial portion of the QRS in V1 and V2, a widened S wave in V5, V6, I and aVL, and with QRS duration greater than or equal to 120 ms.  An RsR' complex is typically present in leads V1 and V2. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: Right Bundle Branch Block by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of a wide QRS complex with evidence of delayed conduction to the right ventricle, manifested by a widened initial portion of the QRS in V1 and V2, a widened S wave in V5, V6, I and aVL, and with QRS duration greater than or equal to 120 ms.  An RsR' complex is typically present in leads V1 and V2. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Right Ventricular Conduction Delay by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Right Ventricular Conduction Delay by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding in which there is evidence that electrical transmission through the right ventricle is impaired with a maximal QRS duration of 110 ms and which does not meet the criteria for Incomplete Right Bundle Branch Block. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: Right Ventricular Conduction Delay by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding in which there is evidence that electrical transmission through the right ventricle is impaired with a maximal QRS duration of 110 ms and which does not meet the criteria for Incomplete Right Bundle Branch Block. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Right Ventricular Hypertrophy by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Right Ventricular Hypertrophy by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding suggestive of a hypertrophied right ventricle, characterized by large R wave amplitudes in the right precordial leads and secondary findings of right atrial enlargement, right axis deviation, and typical pattern of ST depression and T wave inversion in the right precordial leads. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: Right Ventricular Hypertrophy by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding suggestive of a hypertrophied right ventricle, characterized by large R wave amplitudes in the right precordial leads and secondary findings of right atrial enlargement, right axis deviation, and typical pattern of ST depression and T wave inversion in the right precordial leads. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: RSR' by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: RSR' by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding in which there are two R waves, which are two deflections above the baseline resulting from a single ventricular depolarization. The first upward deflection in the complex is the R wave. The S is the first downward deflection. A second upward deflection is called the R-prime wave.

Concepts.longName: RSR' by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding in which there are two R waves, which are two deflections above the baseline resulting from a single ventricular depolarization. The first upward deflection in the complex is the R wave. The S is the first downward deflection. A second upward deflection is called the R-prime wave.

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Septal Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Septal Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding suggesting an infarction in the anatomic location of the cardiac septum.

Concepts.longName: Septal Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding suggesting an infarction in the anatomic location of the cardiac septum.

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Universal Molecular

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Universal Molecular
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A methanol/polyethylene glycol-based fixative that is useful for preservation of DNA, RNA, and proteins. It is particularly useful for preservation of nucleic acids in situ.

Concepts.longName: Short PR Interval by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of an abnormally short PR interval. Thresholds for different age, gender, and patient populations exist. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Short QTc Interval

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Short QTc Interval
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of a QT interval corrected for heart rate that is shorter than the lower limit of normal. Thresholds for different age, gender, and patient populations exist. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: Short QTc Interval
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of a QT interval corrected for heart rate that is shorter than the lower limit of normal. Thresholds for different age, gender, and patient populations exist. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Short ST Segment by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Short ST Segment by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of a short or absent ST segment, resulting in a decreased QT interval, without changes in T wave morphology; this may be observed in hypercalcemia. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: Short ST Segment by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of a short or absent ST segment, resulting in a decreased QT interval, without changes in T wave morphology; this may be observed in hypercalcemia. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Sinus Arrhythmia by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Sinus Arrhythmia by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding in which the sinus rate fluctuates with the respiratory cycle. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: Sinus Arrhythmia by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding in which the sinus rate fluctuates with the respiratory cycle. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Sinus Bradycardia by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Sinus Bradycardia by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of abnormally slow heart rate with its origin in the sinus node. Thresholds for different age, gender, and patient populations exist. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: Sinus Bradycardia by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of abnormally slow heart rate with its origin in the sinus node. Thresholds for different age, gender, and patient populations exist. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Sinus Rhythm

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Sinus Rhythm
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of an atrial rhythm which originates from the sinoatrial node that is considered normal for the population. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: Sinus Rhythm
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of an atrial rhythm which originates from the sinoatrial node that is considered normal for the population. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Sinus Slowing With AV Block by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Sinus Slowing With AV Block by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic tracing demonstrating the simultaneous occurrence of a slowing sinus rate and AV block.

Concepts.longName: Sinus Slowing With AV Block by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic tracing demonstrating the simultaneous occurrence of a slowing sinus rate and AV block.

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Sinus Tachycardia by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Sinus Tachycardia by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of abnormally rapid heart rate with its origin in the sinus node. Thresholds for different age, gender, and patient populations exist. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: Sinus Tachycardia by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of abnormally rapid heart rate with its origin in the sinus node. Thresholds for different age, gender, and patient populations exist. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: ST Elevation Pericarditis by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: ST Elevation Pericarditis by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of ST elevation which is concave upwards, and which is often accompanied by PR segment depression. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: ST Elevation Pericarditis by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of ST elevation which is concave upwards, and which is often accompanied by PR segment depression. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: ST Segment Depression by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: ST Segment Depression by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of ST segment depression below the baseline, often described as up sloping, down sloping or horizontal.

Concepts.longName: ST Segment Depression by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of ST segment depression below the baseline, often described as up sloping, down sloping or horizontal.

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: ST Segment Elevation by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: ST Segment Elevation by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: Evaluation of the interval from the end of ventricular depolarization to the onset of the T wave; it is usually isoelectric in normal subjects.

Concepts.longName: ST Segment Elevation by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of ST segment elevation above the baseline.

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Supraventricular Couplet by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Supraventricular Couplet by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic recording that demonstrates two sequential premature atrial complexes.

Concepts.longName: Supraventricular Couplet by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic recording that demonstrates two sequential premature atrial complexes.

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Supraventricular Escape Beat by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Supraventricular Escape Beat by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of a compensatory supraventricular complex that occurs following a prolonged RR interval. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: Supraventricular Escape Beat by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of a compensatory supraventricular complex that occurs following a prolonged RR interval. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Supraventricular Run by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Supraventricular Run by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic tracing demonstrating three or more consecutive QRS complexes of supraventricular origin, irrespective of rate.

Concepts.longName: Supraventricular Run by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic tracing demonstrating three or more consecutive QRS complexes of supraventricular origin, irrespective of rate.

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Supraventricular Tachycardia by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Supraventricular Tachycardia by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of a tachycardia which does not originate in the ventricles or His Purkinje system. There is an abnormally high heart rate and QRS complexes are typically narrow, but aberration or preexcitation may be present. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: Supraventricular Tachycardia by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of a tachycardia which does not originate in the ventricles or His Purkinje system. There is an abnormally high heart rate and QRS complexes are typically narrow, but aberration or preexcitation may be present. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Sustained Supraventricular Tachycardia by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Sustained Supraventricular Tachycardia by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic tracing demonstrating supraventricular tachycardia of greater than thirty seconds duration. Different thresholds, for rate and/or duration, may apply to different patient populations.

Concepts.longName: Sustained Supraventricular Tachycardia by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic tracing demonstrating supraventricular tachycardia of greater than thirty seconds duration. Different thresholds, for rate and/or duration, may apply to different patient populations.

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Sustained Ventricular Tachycardia by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Sustained Ventricular Tachycardia by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of ventricular tachycardia greater than 30 seconds in duration.

Concepts.longName: Sustained Ventricular Tachycardia by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of ventricular tachycardia greater than 30 seconds in duration.

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: T Wave Alternans by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: T Wave Alternans by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding in which there are variations in the shape, amplitude, or direction of the T wave from one beat to the next.

Concepts.longName: T Wave Alternans by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding in which there are variations in the shape, amplitude, or direction of the T wave from one beat to the next.

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: T Wave Inversion by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: T Wave Inversion by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of an inversion of the T wave from the expected axis.

Concepts.longName: T Wave Inversion by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of an inversion of the T wave from the expected axis.

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: T Wave Notched by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: T Wave Notched by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of an irregular, u or v shaped deflection within the contour of the T wave. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: T Wave Notched by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of an irregular, u or v shaped deflection within the contour of the T wave. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: T Wave Peaked by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: T Wave Peaked by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding in which the T wave appears increased in amplitude and cresting at a point.

Concepts.longName: T Wave Peaked by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding in which the T wave appears increased in amplitude and cresting at a point.

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: T Waves Biphasic by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: T Waves Biphasic by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of a T wave with both positive and negative components. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: T Waves Biphasic by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of a T wave with both positive and negative components. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: T Waves Flat by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: T Waves Flat by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding in which the T wave appears decreased in amplitude.

Concepts.longName: T Waves Flat by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding in which the T wave appears decreased in amplitude.

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Tachycardia by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Tachycardia by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of abnormally rapid heart rate. Thresholds for different age, gender, and patient populations exist.

Concepts.longName: Tachycardia by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of abnormally rapid heart rate. Thresholds for different age, gender, and patient populations exist.

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Torsades De Pointes by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Torsades De Pointes by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of an atypical rapid polymorphic ventricular tachycardia with a characteristic rotation of the QRS complex around the isoelectric baseline, occurring in the setting of a prolonged QT interval. In addition, the QRS complex displays a periodic waxing and waning of amplitude on the electrogram.

Concepts.longName: Torsades De Pointes by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of an atypical rapid polymorphic ventricular tachycardia with a characteristic rotation of the QRS complex around the isoelectric baseline, occurring in the setting of a prolonged QT interval. In addition, the QRS complex displays a periodic waxing and waning of amplitude on the electrocardiogram.

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: U Wave Abnormality by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: U Wave Abnormality by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of U waves which have increased amplitude, are inverted, or merged with the preceding T wave.

Concepts.longName: U Wave Abnormality by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of U waves which have increased amplitude, are inverted, or merged with the preceding T wave.

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Undetermined Rhythm by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Undetermined Rhythm by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of a cardiac rhythm whose mechanism cannot be determined from the ECG. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: Undetermined Rhythm by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of a cardiac rhythm whose mechanism cannot be determined from the ECG. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Undetermined Supraventricular Rhythm by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Undetermined Supraventricular Rhythm by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of a rhythm that cannot be determined from the EKG, but that clearly does not originate in the ventricles or His Purkinje system. Typically, the QRS complexes are narrow, but aberration or preexcitation may be present.

Concepts.longName: Undetermined Supraventricular Rhythm by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of a rhythm that cannot be determined from the EKG, but that clearly does not originate in the ventricles or His Purkinje system. Typically, the QRS complexes are narrow, but aberration or preexcitation may be present.

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Unifocal Atrial Premature Complex by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Unifocal Atrial Premature Complex by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of premature atrial complexes which have a single distinct morphology, suggesting origin at one atrial site.

Concepts.longName: Unifocal Atrial Premature Complex by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of premature atrial complexes which have a single distinct morphology, suggesting origin at one atrial site.

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Unifocal Ventricular Premature Complex by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Unifocal Ventricular Premature Complex by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of premature ventricular complexes which have a single distinct morphology, suggesting origin at one ventricular site.

Concepts.longName: Unifocal Ventricular Premature Complex by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of premature ventricular complexes which have a single distinct morphology, suggesting origin at one ventricular site.

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Bigeminy

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Bigeminy
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of a normal QRS followed by a premature ventricular contraction; a rhythmic pairing of normal and abnormal beats originating in the ventricles in a 1-1 ratio. (NCI)

Concepts.longName: Ventricular Bigeminy by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of a normal QRS followed by a premature ventricular contraction; a rhythmic pairing of normal and atypical beats originating in the ventricles in a 1-1 ratio.

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Ventricular Couplet by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Ventricular Couplet by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding in which two premature ventricular complexes occur sequentially. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: Ventricular Couplet by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding in which two premature ventricular complexes occur sequentially. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Ventricular Escape Beat by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Ventricular Escape Beat by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of a compensatory ventricular complex that occurs following a prolonged RR interval. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: Ventricular Escape Beat by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of a compensatory ventricular complex that occurs following a prolonged RR interval. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Ventricular Fibrillation by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Ventricular Fibrillation by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of a rapid grossly irregular ventricular rhythm with marked variability in QRS cycle length, morphology, and amplitude. The rate is typically greater than 300 bpm. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: Ventricular Fibrillation by ECG Finding
