Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of a rapid grossly irregular ventricular rhythm with marked variability in QRS cycle length, morphology, and amplitude. The rate is typically greater than 300 bpm. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Ventricular Flutter by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Ventricular Flutter by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A ventricular tachyarrhythmia characterized by a high ventricular rate (180 and 250 beats per minute) with a regular rhythm. The electrocardiogram shows large oscillating sine wave-like complexes occurring as a result of QRS complexes and T waves being merged. The P wave is not visible.

Concepts.longName: Ventricular Flutter by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: A ventricular tachyarrhythmia characterized by a high ventricular rate (180 and 250 beats per minute) with a regular rhythm. The electrocardiogram shows large oscillating sine wave-like complexes occurring as a result of QRS complexes and T waves being merged. The P wave is not visible.

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Ventricular Parasystole by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Ventricular Parasystole by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of normal sinus rhythm coexisting with a regular ectopic ventricular rhythm.

Concepts.longName: Ventricular Parasystole by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of normal sinus rhythm coexisting with a regular ectopic ventricular rhythm.

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Premature ventricular contractions (PVCs)

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Premature ventricular contractions (PVCs)
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of a ventricular impulse originating before depolarization has completed.

Concepts.longName: Ventricular Premature Complex by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of an ectopic impulse originating in the ventricles. The QRS morphology of these complexes is different from those of supraventricular origin. The QRS duration is often longer and the RR interval preceding the complexes is usually shorter than that of supraventricular beats. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Ventricular Quadrigeminy by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Ventricular Quadrigeminy by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic tracing demonstrating three normal QRS complexes followed by a premature ventricular contraction over the course of three or more consecutive cycles; a regularly irregular rhythm of normal to abnormal QRS complexes in a 3-1 ratio.

Concepts.longName: Ventricular Quadrigeminy by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic tracing demonstrating three normal QRS complexes followed by a premature ventricular contraction over the course of three or more consecutive cycles; a regularly irregular rhythm of normal to abnormal QRS complexes in a 3-1 ratio.

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Ventricular Repolarization Abnormality

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Ventricular Repolarization Abnormality
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of an abnormality of T wave duration or morphology or of early repolarization. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: Ventricular Repolarization Abnormality
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of an abnormality of T wave duration or morphology or of early repolarization. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Ventricular Run by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Ventricular Run by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic tracing demonstrating three or more consecutive QRS complexes of ventricular origin, irrespective of rate.

Concepts.longName: Ventricular Run by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic tracing demonstrating three or more consecutive QRS complexes of ventricular origin, irrespective of rate.

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Ventricular Tachycardia by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Ventricular Tachycardia by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of three or more consecutive complexes of ventricular organ with a rate greater than a certain threshold (100 or 120 beats per minute are commonly used). The QRS complexes are wide and have an abnormal morphology. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: Ventricular Tachycardia by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of three or more consecutive complexes of ventricular organ with a rate greater than a certain threshold (100 or 120 beats per minute are commonly used). The QRS complexes are wide and have an abnormal morphology. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Trigeminy

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Trigeminy
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of normal QRS followed by a premature ventricular contraction; a rhythmic pairing of normal and atypical beats originating from the ventricles in a 1:2 ratio.

Concepts.longName: Ventricular Trigeminy by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of two sinus beats followed by a premature ventricular complex for 3 or more consecutive cycles; a regularly irregular rhythm of normal and abnormal QRS complexes in a 2-1 ratio. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Wandering Atrial Pacemaker by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Wandering Atrial Pacemaker by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of a supraventricular arrhythmia characterized by 3 or more distinct P wave morphologies with an isoelectric baseline, variable PR intervals and no predominant atrial rhythm. The ventricular rate is typically below 100 beats per minute. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: Wandering Atrial Pacemaker by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of a supraventricular arrhythmia characterized by 3 or more distinct P wave morphologies with an isoelectric baseline, variable PR intervals and no predominant atrial rhythm. The ventricular rate is typically below 100 beats per minute. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Wide QRS Tachycardia by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Wide QRS Tachycardia by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of three or more consecutive wide QRS complexes of uncertain origin with a rate greater than a certain threshold (100 or 120 beats per minute are commonly used). (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: Wide QRS Tachycardia by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of three or more consecutive wide QRS complexes of uncertain origin with a rate greater than a certain threshold (100 or 120 beats per minute are commonly used). (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.value: OLD OR AGE INDETERMINATE WALL MYOCARDIAL INFARCTION
PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Old Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Old Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of pathologic Q waves, which is suggestive of myocardial infarction of one or more regions of the heart, without evidence of current or ongoing acute infarction. No specification is provided for localization. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: Old Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of pathologic Q waves, which is suggestive of myocardial infarction of one or more regions of the heart, without evidence of current or ongoing acute infarction. No specification is provided for localization. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.value: OLD OR AGE INDETERMINATE ANTERIOR WALL MYOCARDIAL INFARCTION
PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Old or Age Indeterminate Anterior Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Old or Age Indeterminate Anterior Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of pathologic Q waves in leads V3 and V4, which is suggestive of myocardial infarction of the anterior wall of the left ventricle, without evidence of current or ongoing acute infarction. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: Old or Age Indeterminate Anterior Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of pathologic Q waves in leads V3 and V4, which is suggestive of myocardial infarction of the anterior wall of the left ventricle, without evidence of current or ongoing acute infarction. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Polymorphic Ventricular Tachycardia by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Polymorphic Ventricular Tachycardia by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of a ventricular tachycardia in which the QRS complexes have a variable morphology and often rate. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: Polymorphic Ventricular Tachycardia by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of a ventricular tachycardia in which the QRS complexes have a variable morphology and often rate. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: 60 Hertz Noise by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: 60 Hertz Noise by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic recording showing power line interference with the electrocardiographic signal. The artifact amplitude modulation has the same frequency as the AC power system present (60 Hz). (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: 60 Hertz Noise by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic recording showing power line interference with the electrocardiographic signal. The artifact amplitude modulation has the same frequency as the AC power system present (60 Hz). (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: 50 Hertz Noise by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: 50 Hertz Noise by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic recording showing power line interference with the electrocardiographic signal. The artifact amplitude modulation has the same frequency as the AC power system present (50 Hz). (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: 50 Hertz Noise by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic recording showing power line interference with the electrocardiographic signal. The artifact amplitude modulation has the same frequency as the AC power system present (50 Hz). (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Aberrantly Conducted Complexes by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Aberrantly Conducted Complexes by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of abnormal QRS complex(es) that are supraventricular in origin, and that are wide secondary to aberrant AV conduction. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: Aberrantly Conducted Complexes by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of abnormal QRS complex(es) that are supraventricular in origin, and that are wide secondary to aberrant AV conduction. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: ACC/AHA Ischemic ECG Changes

ValueMeaning.preferredName: ACC/AHA Ischemic ECG Changes
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding, in the absence of left ventricular hypertrophy (LVH) and left bundle branch block pattern on ECG, of either a) new (or presumed new) ST elevation at the J point in two contiguous leads with the following cut-points: greater than or equal to 0.1 mV in all leads other than leads V2-V3 where the following cut points apply: greater than or equal to 0.2 mV in men age greater than or equal to 40 years, greater than or equal to 0.25 mV in men age greater than 40 years, or greater than or equal to 0.15 mV in women; or b) new (or presumed new) horizontal or down-sloping ST depression greater than or equal to 0.05 mV in two contiguous leads, and/or T wave inversion greater than or equal to 0.1 mV in two contiguous leads with a prominent R wave, or R/S ratio greater than 1. (Thygesen K, Alpert JS, Jaffe AS, et al.: the Writing Group on behalf of the Joint ESC/ACCF/AHA/WHF Task Force for the Universal Definition of Myocardial Infarction. J Am Coll Cardiol 60(16):1-18, 2012)

Concepts.longName: ACC/AHA Ischemic ECG Changes
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding, in the absence of left ventricular hypertrophy (LVH) and left bundle branch block pattern on ECG, of either a) new (or presumed new) ST elevation at the J point in two contiguous leads with the following cut-points: greater than or equal to 0.1 mV in all leads other than leads V2-V3 where the following cut points apply: greater than or equal to 0.2 mV in men age greater than or equal to 40 years, greater than or equal to 0.25 mV in men age greater than 40 years, or greater than or equal to 0.15 mV in women; or b) new (or presumed new) horizontal or down-sloping ST depression greater than or equal to 0.05 mV in two contiguous leads, and/or T wave inversion greater than or equal to 0.1 mV in two contiguous leads with a prominent R wave, or R/S ratio greater than 1. (Thygesen K, Alpert JS, Jaffe AS, et al.: the Writing Group on behalf of the Joint ESC/ACCF/AHA/WHF Task Force for the Universal Definition of Myocardial Infarction. J Am Coll Cardiol 60(16):1-18, 2012)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Accelerated Idioventricular Rhythm by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Accelerated Idioventricular Rhythm by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of idioventricular rhythm with a rate greater than 50 beats per minute. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: Accelerated Idioventricular Rhythm by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of idioventricular rhythm with a rate greater than 50 beats per minute. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Acute Anterior Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Acute Anterior Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of pathologic Q waves with accompanying ST elevation in leads V3 and V4, which is suggestive of acute myocardial infarction of the anterior wall of the left ventricle. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: Acute Anterior Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of pathologic Q waves with accompanying ST elevation in leads V3 and V4, which is suggestive of acute myocardial infarction of the anterior wall of the left ventricle. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Acute Anterolateral Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Acute Anterolateral Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of pathologic Q waves with accompanying ST elevation in leads V3 through V6, which is suggestive of acute myocardial infarction of the anterolateral wall of the left ventricle. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: Acute Anterolateral Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of pathologic Q waves with accompanying ST elevation in leads V3 through V6, which is suggestive of acute myocardial infarction of the anterolateral wall of the left ventricle. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Acute Anteroseptal Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Acute Anteroseptal Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of pathologic Q waves with accompanying ST elevation in leads V1 through V4, which is suggestive of acute myocardial infarction of the anteroseptal wall of the left ventricle. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: Acute Anteroseptal Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of pathologic Q waves with accompanying ST elevation in leads V1 through V4, which is suggestive of acute myocardial infarction of the anteroseptal wall of the left ventricle. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.value: ACUTE EXTENSIVE ANTERIOR WALL MYOCARDIAL INFARCTION
PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Acute Extensive Anterior Wall Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Acute Extensive Anterior Wall Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of pathologic Q waves with accompanying ST elevation in leads V1 to V6, I and aVL, which is suggestive of acute myocardial infarction involving the anterior and anterolateral walls of the left ventricle.

Concepts.longName: Acute Extensive Anterior Wall Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of pathologic Q waves with accompanying ST elevation in leads V1 to V6, I and aVL, which is suggestive of acute myocardial infarction involving the anterior and anterolateral walls of the left ventricle. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.value: ACUTE HIGH LATERAL WALL MYOCARDIAL INFARCTION
PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Acute High Lateral Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Acute High Lateral Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of pathologic Q waves with accompanying ST elevation in leads I and aVL, which is suggestive of acute myocardial infarction of the high lateral wall of the left ventricle. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: Acute High Lateral Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of pathologic Q waves with accompanying ST elevation in leads I and aVL, which is suggestive of acute myocardial infarction of the high lateral wall of the left ventricle. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Acute Inferior Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Acute Inferior Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of pathologic Q waves with accompanying ST elevation in leads III, aVF and often II, which is suggestive of acute myocardial infarction of the inferior wall of the left ventricle. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: Acute Inferior Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of pathologic Q waves with accompanying ST elevation in leads III, aVF and often II, which is suggestive of acute myocardial infarction of the inferior wall of the left ventricle. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Acute Lateral Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Acute Lateral Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of pathologic Q waves with accompanying ST elevation in leads V5, V6, I and aVL, which is suggestive of acute myocardial infarction of the lateral wall of the left ventricle. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: Acute Lateral Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of pathologic Q waves with accompanying ST elevation in leads V5, V6, I and aVL, which is suggestive of acute myocardial infarction of the lateral wall of the left ventricle. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Acute Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Acute Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding showing a current of injury with ST elevation. No specification is provided for localization. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: Acute Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding showing a current of injury with ST elevation. No specification is provided for localization. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Acute Posterior Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Acute Posterior Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding in leads V1 or V2 of an initial R wave duration greater than or equal to 40 ms, R wave greater than S wave, upright T wave, with accompanying ST elevation, which is suggestive of acute myocardial infarction of the posterior wall of the left ventricle. Evidence of inferior or lateral myocardial infarction is usually also present. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: Acute Posterior Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding in leads V1 or V2 of an initial R wave duration greater than or equal to 40 ms, R wave greater than S wave, upright T wave, with accompanying ST elevation, which is suggestive of acute myocardial infarction of the posterior wall of the left ventricle. Evidence of inferior or lateral myocardial infarction is usually also present. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.value: ACUTE RIGHT VENTRICULAR WALL MYOCARDIAL INFARCTION
PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Acute Right Ventricular Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Acute Right Ventricular Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding in leads V1 or V2 of an initial R wave duration greater than or equal to 40 ms, R wave greater than S wave, upright T wave, with accompanying ST elevation, which is suggestive of acute myocardial infarction of the ventricular wall of the left ventricle. Evidence of inferior or lateral myocardial infarction is usually also present. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: Acute Right Ventricular Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding in leads V1 or V2 of an initial R wave duration greater than or equal to 40 ms, R wave greater than S wave, upright T wave, with accompanying ST elevation, which is suggestive of acute myocardial infarction of the ventricular wall of the left ventricle. Evidence of inferior or lateral myocardial infarction is usually also present. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Acute Septal Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Acute Septal Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of pathologic Q waves with accompanying ST elevation in leads V1, V2 and often V3, which is suggestive of acute myocardial infarction of the intraventricular septum. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: Acute Septal Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of pathologic Q waves with accompanying ST elevation in leads V1, V2 and often V3, which is suggestive of acute myocardial infarction of the intraventricular septum. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: All Precordial Electrodes Are Disconnected by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: All Precordial Electrodes Are Disconnected by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic recording in which all precordial electrodes are disconnected resulting in missing waveforms (flat line) of all leads V1 - V6. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: All Precordial Electrodes Are Disconnected by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic recording in which all precordial electrodes are disconnected resulting in missing waveforms (flat line) of all leads V1 - V6. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Alternating Current Noise by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Alternating Current Noise by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic recording showing power line interference with the electrocardiographic signal. The artifact amplitude modulation has the same frequency as the AC power system present (usually 50 Hz or 60 Hz). (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: Alternating Current Noise by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic recording showing power line interference with the electrocardiographic signal. The artifact amplitude modulation has the same frequency as the AC power system present (usually 50 Hz or 60 Hz). (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Anterior Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Anterior Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of pathologic Q waves in leads V3 and V4, which is suggestive of myocardial infarction of the anterior wall of the left ventricle. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: Anterior Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of pathologic Q waves in leads V3 and V4, which is suggestive of myocardial infarction of the anterior wall of the left ventricle. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Anterolateral Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Anterolateral Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of pathologic Q waves in leads V3 through V6, which is suggestive of myocardial infarction of the anterolateral wall of the left ventricle. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: Anterolateral Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of pathologic Q waves in leads V3 through V6, which is suggestive of myocardial infarction of the anterolateral wall of the left ventricle. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Anteroseptal Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Anteroseptal Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of pathologic Q waves in leads V1 through V4, which is suggestive of myocardial infarction of the anteroseptal wall of the left ventricle. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: Anteroseptal Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of pathologic Q waves in leads V1 through V4, which is suggestive of myocardial infarction of the anteroseptal wall of the left ventricle. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Artifact Lead Signal by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Artifact Lead Signal by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic recording in which one or more leads display extraneous signals which do not represent cardiac electrical activity. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: Artifact Lead Signal by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic recording in which one or more leads display extraneous signals which do not represent cardiac electrical activity. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Asystole by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Asystole by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding showing no cardiac electrical activity on the monitor or printed strip for the entire duration of the recording. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: Asystole by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding showing no cardiac electrical activity on the monitor or printed strip for the entire duration of the recording. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Atrial Bigeminy by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Atrial Bigeminy by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of a sinus beat followed by a premature atrial complexes for three or more consecutive cycles; a regularly irregular rhythm of normal and abnormal P waves in a 1-1 ratio. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: Atrial Bigeminy by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of a sinus beat followed by a premature atrial complexes for three or more consecutive cycles; a regularly irregular rhythm of normal and abnormal P waves in a 1-1 ratio. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Atrial Couplet by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Atrial Couplet by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding in which two premature atrial complexes occur sequentially. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: Atrial Couplet by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding in which two premature atrial complexes occur sequentially. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Atrial Enlargement by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Atrial Enlargement by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding which comprises left, right or bilateral atrial enlargement. This is may be characterized by prolonged P wave duration, increased P wave amplitude, or multi-component P waves. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: Atrial Enlargement by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding which comprises left, right or bilateral atrial enlargement. This is may be characterized by prolonged P wave duration, increased P wave amplitude, or multi-component P waves. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Atrial Fibrillation by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Atrial Fibrillation by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of a supraventricular arrhythmia characterized by the replacement of consistent P waves by rapid oscillations or fibrillatory waves that vary in size, shape and timing and are accompanied by an irregularly irregular ventricular response. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: Atrial Fibrillation by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of a supraventricular arrhythmia characterized by the replacement of consistent P waves by rapid oscillations or fibrillatory waves that vary in size, shape and timing and are accompanied by an irregularly irregular ventricular response. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Atrial Flutter by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Atrial Flutter by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of an organized, regular atrial rhythm with atrial rate of 240-340 beats per minute. Multiple P waves typically appear in the inferior leads in a saw tooth like pattern between the QRS complexes. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: Atrial Flutter by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of an organized, regular atrial rhythm with atrial rate of 240-340 beats per minute. Multiple P waves typically appear in the inferior leads in a saw tooth like pattern between the QRS complexes. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Atrial Premature Complex by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Atrial Premature Complex by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of an ectopic impulse originating in the atria and not specifically in the sinus node. The P wave morphology of these complexes is often different from a sinus P wave and the RR intervals preceding these complexes is also shorter than those of the regular beats. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: Atrial Premature Complex by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of an ectopic impulse originating in the atria and not specifically in the sinus node. The P wave morphology of these complexes is often different from a sinus P wave and the RR intervals preceding these complexes is also shorter than those of the regular beats. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Atrial Tachycardia by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Atrial Tachycardia by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of an organized, regular atrial rhythm with atrial rate between 101 and 240 beats per minute. The P wave morphology must be distinct from the sinus P wave morphology. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: Atrial Tachycardia by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of an organized, regular atrial rhythm with atrial rate between 101 and 240 beats per minute. The P wave morphology must be distinct from the sinus P wave morphology. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Atrial Tachycardia With AV Block by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Atrial Tachycardia With AV Block by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic recording that demonstrates atrial tachycardia without 1:1 atrioventricular conduction.

Concepts.longName: Atrial Tachycardia With AV Block by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic recording that demonstrates atrial tachycardia without 1:1 atrioventricular conduction.

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Atrial Trigeminy by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Atrial Trigeminy by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of two sinus beats followed by a premature atrial complex for 3 or more consecutive cycles; a regularly irregular rhythm of normal and abnormal P waves in a 2-1 ratio. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: Atrial Trigeminy by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of two sinus beats followed by a premature atrial complex for 3 or more consecutive cycles; a regularly irregular rhythm of normal and abnormal P waves in a 2-1 ratio. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Atrioventricular Dissociation by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Atrioventricular Dissociation by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding in which the electrical activity of the atria and ventricles are independent of one another. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: Atrioventricular Dissociation by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding in which the electrical activity of the atria and ventricles are independent of one another. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: AV Block First Degree by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: AV Block First Degree by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of prolonged PR interval for a specific population. For adults one common threshold is a PR interval greater than 0.20 seconds. Note that other thresholds may be applicable. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: AV Block First Degree by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of prolonged PR interval for a specific population. For adults one common threshold is a PR interval greater than 0.20 seconds. Note that other thresholds may be applicable. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: AV Block Second Degree by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: AV Block Second Degree by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of intermittent failure of atrial electrical impulse conduction to the ventricles. This is manifest on the ECG by regular P waves which intermittently are not followed by QRS complexes. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: AV Block Second Degree by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of intermittent failure of atrial electrical impulse conduction to the ventricles. This is manifest on the ECG by regular P waves which intermittently are not followed by QRS complexes. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: AV Block Second Degree Mobitz Type I by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: AV Block Second Degree Mobitz Type I by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of intermittent failure of atrial electrical impulse conduction to the ventricles, characterized by a progressively lengthening PR interval prior to the block of an atrial impulse. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: AV Block Second Degree Mobitz Type I by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of intermittent failure of atrial electrical impulse conduction to the ventricles, characterized by a progressively lengthening PR interval prior to the block of an atrial impulse. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: AV Block Second Degree Mobitz Type II by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: AV Block Second Degree Mobitz Type II by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of intermittent failure of atrial electrical impulse conduction to the ventricles, characterized by a relatively constant PR interval prior to the block of an atrial impulse.

Concepts.longName: AV Block Second Degree Mobitz Type II by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of intermittent failure of atrial electrical impulse conduction to the ventricles, characterized by a relatively constant PR interval prior to the block of an atrial impulse.

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: AV Block Third Degree by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: AV Block Third Degree by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of complete failure of atrial electrical impulse conduction to the ventricles. This is manifested on the ECG by disassociation of atrial and ventricular rhythms. The atrial rate must be faster than the ventricular rate. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: AV Block Third Degree by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of complete failure of atrial electrical impulse conduction to the ventricles. This is manifested on the ECG by disassociation of atrial and ventricular rhythms. The atrial rate must be faster than the ventricular rate. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Baseline Wander by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Baseline Wander by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic recording in which the isoelectric line in one or more leads is vertically displaced resulting in low frequency upward and downward movements of the signal with varying amplitudes. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: Baseline Wander by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic recording in which the isoelectric line in one or more leads is vertically displaced resulting in low frequency upward and downward movements of the signal with varying amplitudes. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Bifascicular Block by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Bifascicular Block by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding comprising right bundle branch block and left anterior fascicular block, or right bundle branch block and left posterior fascicular block. Defects occurring in two of the three divisions of the conduction system of the heart are considered bifascicular blocks. Technically left bundle branch block may be considered a bifascicular block.

Concepts.longName: Bifascicular Block by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding comprising right bundle branch block and left anterior fascicular block, or right bundle branch block and left posterior fascicular block. Defects occurring in two of the three divisions of the conduction system of the heart are considered bifascicular blocks. Technically left bundle branch block may be considered a bifascicular block.

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Biventricular Hypertrophy by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Biventricular Hypertrophy by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding suggestive of enlargement or thickening of both ventricles, with a combination of findings which are related to LVH and RVH, such as voltage criteria for LVH in the presence of marked right axis deviation. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: Biventricular Hypertrophy by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding suggestive of enlargement or thickening of both ventricles, with a combination of findings which are related to LVH and RVH, such as voltage criteria for LVH in the presence of marked right axis deviation. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Blocked Atrial Premature Complex by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Blocked Atrial Premature Complex by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of premature atrial complexes which are not conducted to the ventricle, and which are not followed by a QRS complex. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: Blocked Atrial Premature Complex by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of premature atrial complexes which are not conducted to the ventricle, and which are not followed by a QRS complex. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Borderline QTcB

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Borderline QTcB
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding in which the QT interval corrected for heart rate using Bazett's formula is slightly prolonged. Thresholds for different age, gender, and patient populations exist. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: Borderline QTcB
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding in which the QT interval corrected for heart rate using Bazett's formula is slightly prolonged. Thresholds for different age, gender, and patient populations exist. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Borderline QTcF

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Borderline QTcF
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding in which the QT interval corrected for heart rate using Fridericia's formula is slightly prolonged. Thresholds for different age, gender, and patient populations exist. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: Borderline QTcF
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding in which the QT interval corrected for heart rate using Fridericia's formula is slightly prolonged. Thresholds for different age, gender, and patient populations exist. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Bradycardia by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Bradycardia by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of abnormally slow heart rate. Thresholds for different age, gender, and patient populations exist.

Concepts.longName: Bradycardia by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of abnormally slow heart rate. Thresholds for different age, gender, and patient populations exist.

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Brugada Syndrome Pattern by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Brugada Syndrome Pattern by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of complete or incomplete right bundle branch block accompanied by ST elevation in leads V1-V3. This may be noted at rest or can be provoked by medication challenge. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: Brugada Syndrome Pattern by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of complete or incomplete right bundle branch block accompanied by ST elevation in leads V1-V3. This may be noted at rest or can be provoked by medication challenge. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Corrected Prolonged QT Interval by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Corrected Prolonged QT Interval by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding in which the QTc interval corrected for heart rate is prolonged. Thresholds for different age, gender, and patient populations exist. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: Corrected Prolonged QT Interval by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding in which the QTc interval corrected for heart rate is prolonged. Thresholds for different age, gender, and patient populations exist. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Defibrillator Discharge by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Defibrillator Discharge by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic tracing that is generated by cardioversion or defibrillation.

Concepts.longName: Defibrillator Discharge by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic tracing that is generated by cardioversion or defibrillation.

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Delta Wave by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Delta Wave by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of initial slurring (delta wave) of the QRS complex due to the presence of an accessory pathway. This characteristic ECG pattern is typically seen in Wolff-Parkinson-White syndrome. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: Delta Wave by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of initial slurring (delta wave) of the QRS complex due to the presence of an accessory pathway. This characteristic ECG pattern is typically seen in Wolff-Parkinson-White syndrome. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Dextrocardia by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Dextrocardia by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding suggestive of dextrocardia with situs inversus, characterized by reversal of normal anterior R wave progression and the appearance of reversal of the right and left arm electrodes. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: Dextrocardia by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding suggestive of dextrocardia with situs inversus, characterized by reversal of normal anterior R wave progression and the appearance of reversal of the right and left arm electrodes. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Disconnected Precordial Electrode V1 by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Disconnected Precordial Electrode V1 by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic recording in which the electrode for lead V1 is disconnected resulting in missing waveforms (flat line) for lead V1. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: Disconnected Precordial Electrode V1 by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic recording in which the electrode for lead V1 is disconnected resulting in missing waveforms (flat line) for lead V1. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Disconnected Precordial Electrode V2 by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Disconnected Precordial Electrode V2 by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic recording in which the electrode for lead V2 is disconnected resulting in missing waveforms (flat line) for lead V2. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: Disconnected Precordial Electrode V2 by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic recording in which the electrode for lead V2 is disconnected resulting in missing waveforms (flat line) for lead V2. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Disconnected Precordial Electrode V3 by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Disconnected Precordial Electrode V3 by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic recording in which the electrode for lead V3 is disconnected resulting in missing waveforms (flat line) for lead V3. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: Disconnected Precordial Electrode V3 by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic recording in which the electrode for lead V3 is disconnected resulting in missing waveforms (flat line) for lead V3. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Disconnected Precordial Electrode V4 by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Disconnected Precordial Electrode V4 by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic recording in which the electrode for lead V4 is disconnected resulting in missing waveforms (flat line) for lead V4. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: Disconnected Precordial Electrode V4 by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic recording in which the electrode for lead V4 is disconnected resulting in missing waveforms (flat line) for lead V4. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Disconnected Precordial Electrode V5 by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Disconnected Precordial Electrode V5 by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic recording in which the electrode for lead V5 is disconnected resulting in missing waveforms (flat line) for lead V5. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: Disconnected Precordial Electrode V5 by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic recording in which the electrode for lead V5 is disconnected resulting in missing waveforms (flat line) for lead V5. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Disconnected Precordial Electrode V6 by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Disconnected Precordial Electrode V6 by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic recording in which the electrode for lead V6 is disconnected resulting in missing waveforms (flat line) for lead V6. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: Disconnected Precordial Electrode V6 by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic recording in which the electrode for lead V6 is disconnected resulting in missing waveforms (flat line) for lead V6. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Early R Wave Transition by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Early R Wave Transition by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding where the amplitude of the R wave becomes greater than the amplitude of the S wave in the QRS complex at an unusually early point in the precordial leads, usually in leads V1 or V2. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: Early R Wave Transition by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding where the amplitude of the R wave becomes greater than the amplitude of the S wave in the QRS complex at an unusually early point in the precordial leads, usually in leads V1 or V2. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Early Repolarization

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Early Repolarization
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of J point and ST segment elevation in the absence of other signs of acute ischemia or pericarditis. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: Early Repolarization
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of J point and ST segment elevation in the absence of other signs of acute ischemia or pericarditis. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.value: ECG ACQUIRED WITH PRECORDIAL ELECTRODES PLACED ON RIGHT CHEST
PermissibleValues.valueDescription: ECG Acquired with Precordial Electrodes Placed on the Right Chest

ValueMeaning.preferredName: ECG Acquired with Precordial Electrodes Placed on the Right Chest
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic recording in which the precordial electrodes have been placed over the right chest and record a right sided ECG. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: ECG Acquired with Precordial Electrodes Placed on the Right Chest
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic recording in which the precordial electrodes have been placed over the right chest and record a right sided ECG. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.value: ECG EVALUATION NOT PERFORMED DUE TO CORRUPTED DIGITAL ECG FILE
PermissibleValues.valueDescription: ECG Evaluation Not Performed Due to Corrupted Digital ECG File

ValueMeaning.preferredName: ECG Evaluation Not Performed Due to Corrupted Digital ECG File
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A digital electrocardiographic recording which is corrupted (i.e. ECG signal cannot be restored) such that measurements and/or interpretation cannot be performed. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: ECG Evaluation Not Performed Due to Corrupted Digital ECG File
Concepts.definition: A digital electrocardiographic recording which is corrupted (i.e. ECG signal cannot be restored) such that measurements and/or interpretation cannot be performed. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.value: ECG EVALUATION NOT PERFORMED DUE TO POOR QUALITY OF PRINTED ECG
PermissibleValues.valueDescription: ECG Evaluation Not Performed Due to Poor Quality of Printed ECG

ValueMeaning.preferredName: ECG Evaluation Not Performed Due to Poor Quality of Printed ECG
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A printed electrocardiographic recording with poor printout quality (e.g. a faded paper ECG tracing or ECG with inconsistent printing speed) such that measurements and/or interpretation cannot be performed. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: ECG Evaluation Not Performed Due to Poor Quality of Printed ECG
Concepts.definition: A printed electrocardiographic recording with poor printout quality (e.g. a faded paper ECG tracing or ECG with inconsistent printing speed) such that measurements and/or interpretation cannot be performed. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.value: ECG EVALUATION NOT PERFORMED DUE TO UNKNOWN ECG AMPLITUDE GAIN OR RECORDING SPEED
PermissibleValues.valueDescription: ECG Evaluation Not Performed Due to Unknown ECG Amplitude Gain or Recording Speed

ValueMeaning.preferredName: ECG Evaluation Not Performed Due to Unknown ECG Amplitude Gain or Recording Speed
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic recording in which measurements and/or interpretation are not performed because the ECG amplitude gain and/or recording speed are not known. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: ECG Evaluation Not Performed Due to Unknown ECG Amplitude Gain or Recording Speed
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic recording in which measurements and/or interpretation are not performed because the ECG amplitude gain and/or recording speed are not known. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: ECG Waveforms Not Present

ValueMeaning.preferredName: ECG Waveforms Not Present
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic recording that displays flat lines (no waveforms are visible) in all leads present. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: ECG Waveforms Not Present
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic recording that displays flat lines (no waveforms are visible) in all leads present. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Ectopic Atrial Rhythm by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Ectopic Atrial Rhythm by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of a regular atrial rhythm with atrial rate of less than 101 beats per minute which does not originate in the sinus node, and which is characterized by P waves whose morphology differs from the P wave morphology during sinus rhythm. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: Ectopic Atrial Rhythm by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of a regular atrial rhythm with atrial rate of less than 101 beats per minute which does not originate in the sinus node, and which is characterized by P waves whose morphology differs from the P wave morphology during sinus rhythm. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Ectopic Ventricular Rhythm by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Ectopic Ventricular Rhythm by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of three or more consecutive complexes of ventricular origin. The QRS complexes are wide and have an abnormal morphology. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: Ectopic Ventricular Rhythm by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of three or more consecutive complexes of ventricular origin. The QRS complexes are wide and have an abnormal morphology. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Electrical Alternans by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Electrical Alternans by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding in which there is an alternating pattern of any of the waveform components.

Concepts.longName: Electrical Alternans by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding in which there is an alternating pattern of any of the waveform components.

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Exit Block by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Exit Block by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding in which impaired conduction or automaticity within the sinus node results in the failure of impulse transmission from the sinoatrial node. This is manifested as dropped P waves during sinus rhythm. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: Exit Block by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding in which impaired conduction or automaticity within the sinus node results in the failure of impulse transmission from the sinoatrial node. This is manifested as dropped P waves during sinus rhythm. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Extensive Anterior Wall Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Extensive Anterior Wall Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of pathologic Q waves in leads V1 to V6, I and aVL, which is suggestive of myocardial infarction involving the anterior and anterolateral walls of the left ventricle. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: Extensive Anterior Wall Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of pathologic Q waves in leads V1 to V6, I and aVL, which is suggestive of myocardial infarction involving the anterior and anterolateral walls of the left ventricle. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Extreme Right Axis Deviation

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Extreme Right Axis Deviation
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of a frontal plane QRS axis from -90 to +180 degrees. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: Extreme Right Axis Deviation
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of a frontal plane QRS axis from -90 to +180 degrees. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Frequent Premature Atrial Complexes by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Frequent Premature Atrial Complexes by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic tracing demonstrating frequent premature atrial contractions that exceed an acceptable, predetermined threshold. Different thresholds may apply to different patient populations.

Concepts.longName: Frequent Premature Atrial Complexes by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic tracing demonstrating frequent premature atrial contractions that exceed an acceptable, predetermined threshold. Different thresholds may apply to different patient populations.

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Frequent Premature Ventricular Complexes by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Frequent Premature Ventricular Complexes by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic tracing demonstrating frequent premature ventricular contractions that exceed an acceptable, predetermined threshold. Different thresholds may apply to different patient populations.

Concepts.longName: Frequent Premature Ventricular Complexes by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic tracing demonstrating frequent premature ventricular contractions that exceed an acceptable, predetermined threshold. Different thresholds may apply to different patient populations.

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Fusion Complex

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Fusion Complex
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding that occurs when electrical activation of the atria or ventricles occurs from two separate sites. This results in a P wave or QRS complex that displays merged characteristics of beats originating from the two different sites. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: Fusion Complex
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding that occurs when electrical activation of the atria or ventricles occurs from two separate sites. This results in a P wave or QRS complex that displays merged characteristics of beats originating from the two different sites. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: High Lateral Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: High Lateral Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of pathologic Q waves in leads I and aVL, which is suggestive of myocardial infarction of the high lateral wall of the left ventricle. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: High Lateral Myocardial Infarction by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of pathologic Q waves in leads I and aVL, which is suggestive of myocardial infarction of the high lateral wall of the left ventricle. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Holter Lead Fail by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Holter Lead Fail by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A continuous, ambulatory electrocardiographic recording during which one or more electrodes are disconnected, at least temporarily, resulting in one or more invalid ECG waveforms.

Concepts.longName: Holter Lead Fail by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: A continuous, ambulatory electrocardiographic recording during which one or more electrodes are disconnected, at least temporarily, resulting in one or more invalid ECG waveforms.

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Idioventricular Rhythm

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Idioventricular Rhythm
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of a cardiac rhythm originating in the ventricles. The heart rate is usually regular and ranging between 30-40 beats per minute (the intrinsic ventricular rate), but can be higher or lower.

Concepts.longName: Idioventricular Rhythm
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of three or more consecutive complexes of ventricular origin with a rate less than a certain threshold (100 or 120 beats per minute are commonly used). The QRS complexes are wide and have an abnormal morphology. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Inability to Digitize ECG Leads

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Inability to Digitize ECG Leads
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A statement indicating the inability to digitize a paper ECG. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: Inability to Digitize ECG Leads
Concepts.definition: A statement indicating the inability to digitize a paper ECG. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Incomplete ECG

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Incomplete ECG
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic recording which is limited in duration or which does not display all of the expected leads. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: Incomplete ECG
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic recording which is limited in duration or which does not display all of the expected leads. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.value: INCOMPLETE MEASUREMENTS DUE TO TRUNCATION OF QRS COMPLEXES
PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Incomplete ECG Measurements Due to Truncation of QRS Complexes

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Incomplete ECG Measurements Due to Truncation of QRS Complexes
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic recording in which measurements (particularly of QRS amplitudes) and/or interpretations are not performed because QRS complexes have been truncated. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: Incomplete ECG Measurements Due to Truncation of QRS Complexes
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic recording in which measurements (particularly of QRS amplitudes) and/or interpretations are not performed because QRS complexes have been truncated. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: 2:1 Atrioventricular Block by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: 2:1 Atrioventricular Block by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of a supraventricular rhythm where the ratio of impulses generated above the atrioventricular node to the number of impulses conducted through to the ventricles is 2:1. This is manifested on the ECG as 2 P waves per QRS complex. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: 2:1 Atrioventricular Block by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of a supraventricular rhythm where the ratio of impulses generated above the atrioventricular node to the number of impulses conducted through to the ventricles is 2:1. This is manifested on the ECG as 2 P waves per QRS complex. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: High Grade Atrioventricular Block by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: High Grade Atrioventricular Block by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of intermittent failure of atrial electrical impulse conduction to the ventricles, characterized by two or more consecutive non-conducted P waves. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: High Grade Atrioventricular Block by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of intermittent failure of atrial electrical impulse conduction to the ventricles, characterized by two or more consecutive non-conducted P waves. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Atrioventricular Nodal Reentry Tachycardia by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Atrioventricular Nodal Reentry Tachycardia by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of a regular supraventricular tachycardia due to reentry within the AV node. It is characterized by P waves which typically occur nearly simultaneously with the QRS complex, resulting in a P wave which is obscured by the QRS, merged with the QRS or which may follow the QRS. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: Atrioventricular Nodal Reentry Tachycardia by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of a regular supraventricular tachycardia due to reentry within the AV node. It is characterized by P waves which typically occur nearly simultaneously with the QRS complex, resulting in a P wave which is obscured by the QRS, merged with the QRS or which may follow the QRS. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Atrioventricular Reentrant Tachycardia by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Atrioventricular Reentrant Tachycardia by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of a regular supraventricular tachycardia which utilizes an atrioventricular bypass tract as its retrograde limb (orthodromic tachycardia) or as its antegrade limb (antidromic tachycardia). QRS complexes during sinus rhythm may show preexcitation. During orthodromic tachycardia the preexcitation is not present and a retrograde P wave may appear after the QRS complex. During antidromic tachycardia the QRS complex is preexcited. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: Atrioventricular Reentrant Tachycardia by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of a regular supraventricular tachycardia which utilizes an atrioventricular bypass tract as its retrograde limb (orthodromic tachycardia) or as its antegrade limb (antidromic tachycardia). QRS complexes during sinus rhythm may show preexcitation. During orthodromic tachycardia the preexcitation is not present and a retrograde P wave may appear after the QRS complex. During antidromic tachycardia the QRS complex is preexcited. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Incompletely Digitized ECG Leads

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Incompletely Digitized ECG Leads
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A digital electrocardiographic recording which was digitized from paper ECG tracings and which does not contain all leads present on the original paper printout. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: Incompletely Digitized ECG Leads
Concepts.definition: A digital electrocardiographic recording which was digitized from paper ECG tracings and which does not contain all leads present on the original paper printout. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Incorrectly Scaled ECG

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Incorrectly Scaled ECG
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic recording in which the ECG signal is not displayed at the indicated recording speed and/or amplitude resolution. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: Incorrectly Scaled ECG
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic recording in which the ECG signal is not displayed at the indicated recording speed and/or amplitude resolution. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Nonspecific Intraventricular Conduction Delay by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Nonspecific Intraventricular Conduction Delay by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of a widened QRS duration typically greater than 110 ms which does not meet the morphologic criteria for any of the standard bundle branch or fascicular block patterns. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: Nonspecific Intraventricular Conduction Delay by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of a widened QRS duration typically greater than 110 ms which does not meet the morphologic criteria for any of the standard bundle branch or fascicular block patterns. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Disconnected Limb Electrodes by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Disconnected Limb Electrodes by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic recording in which one or more of the limb electrodes are disconnected resulting in missing waveforms (often flat lines) of the respective leads. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: Disconnected Limb Electrodes by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic recording in which one or more of the limb electrodes are disconnected resulting in missing waveforms (often flat lines) of the respective leads. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Low Voltage in Limb Leads Only by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Low Voltage in Limb Leads Only by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of small QRS amplitudes (less than 500 microvolts) in all limb leads.

Concepts.longName: Low Voltage in Limb Leads Only by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of small QRS amplitudes (less than 500 microvolts) in all limb leads. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Non-Diagnostic Q Waves by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Non-Diagnostic Q Waves by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of Q waves that are insufficient for the diagnosis of myocardial infarction. In such cases, a myocardial infarction may be suspected even though ECG diagnostic criteria are absent. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: Non-Diagnostic Q Waves by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of Q waves that are insufficient for the diagnosis of myocardial infarction. In such cases, a myocardial infarction may be suspected even though ECG diagnostic criteria are absent. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Non-Specific ST-T Changes by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Non-Specific ST-T Changes by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of changes in the ST segment and T wave that do not meet criteria for ischemia or infarction.

Concepts.longName: Non-Specific ST-T Changes by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of changes in the ST segment and T wave that do not meet criteria for ischemia or infarction.

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Non-Sustained Atrial Tachycardia by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Non-Sustained Atrial Tachycardia by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of an atrial tachycardia which terminates in less than 30 seconds. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: Non-Sustained Atrial Tachycardia by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of an atrial tachycardia which terminates in less than 30 seconds. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Non-Sustained Ventricular Tachycardia by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Non-Sustained Ventricular Tachycardia by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of ventricular tachycardia less than 30 seconds in duration.

Concepts.longName: Non-Sustained Ventricular Tachycardia by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of ventricular tachycardia less than 30 seconds in duration.

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Pre-Excitation Syndrome

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Pre-Excitation Syndrome
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A syndrome characterized by premature contractions of the ventricles due to the presence of an accessory conductive pathway between the atria and the ventricles.

Concepts.longName: Pre-Excitation Syndrome
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding characterized by a premature activation of the whole or some part of the ventricle. The PR interval is usually shortened and delta waves are frequently present. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Incorrectly Positioned Precordial Electrodes by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Incorrectly Positioned Precordial Electrodes by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic recording in which one or more precordial electrodes are placed incorrectly with respect to the standard chest electrode positions resulting in improper representation of the affected leads. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: Incorrectly Positioned Precordial Electrodes by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic recording in which one or more precordial electrodes are placed incorrectly with respect to the standard chest electrode positions resulting in improper representation of the affected leads. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Q Axis Left Axis Deviation

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Q Axis Left Axis Deviation
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of the Q axis from -30 to -90 degrees.

Concepts.longName: Q Axis Left Axis Deviation
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of the Q axis from -30 to -90 degrees.

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Q Axis Right Axis Deviation

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Q Axis Right Axis Deviation
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of the Q axis from +90 to +180 degrees.

Concepts.longName: Q Axis Right Axis Deviation
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of the Q axis from +90 to +180 degrees.

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Sinus Arrest by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Sinus Arrest by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding in which a failure of impulse formation or conduction in the sinus node produces prolongation of the P-P interval or dropped P waves. The threshold for the prolongation of the P-P interval is not well defined. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: Sinus Arrest by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding in which a failure of impulse formation or conduction in the sinus node produces prolongation of the P-P interval or dropped P waves. The threshold for the prolongation of the P-P interval is not well defined. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Supraventricular Premature Complex With Unknown Origin by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Supraventricular Premature Complex With Unknown Origin by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of an ectopic impulse originating from the atria or atrioventricular junction for which the site of origin cannot be determined from the surface electrocardiographic recording; there may be one or more occurrences during an electrocardiographic recording.

Concepts.longName: Supraventricular Premature Complex With Unknown Origin by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of an ectopic impulse originating from the atria or atrioventricular junction for which the site of origin cannot be determined from the surface electrocardiographic recording; there may be one or more occurrences during an electrocardiographic recording.

PermissibleValues.value: SUSPECT LIMB ELECTRODES REVERSED, INTERPRETATION ASSUMES NO REVERSAL
PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Suspicion of Limb Electrodes Reversal But Interpretation Assumes No Reversal by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Suspicion of Limb Electrodes Reversal But Interpretation Assumes No Reversal by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic recording in which an interchange of one or more limb lead electrodes is suspected, but for which an interpretation is performed as though the lead placement is correct. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: Suspicion of Limb Electrodes Reversal But Interpretation Assumes No Reversal by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic recording in which an interchange of one or more limb lead electrodes is suspected, but for which an interpretation is performed as though the lead placement is correct. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.value: SUSPECT LIMB ELECTRODES REVERSED, INTERPRETATION ASSUMES REVERSAL
PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Suspicion of Limb Electrodes Reversal But Interpretation Assumes Reversal by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Suspicion of Limb Electrodes Reversal But Interpretation Assumes Reversal by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic recording in which an interchange of one or more limb lead electrodes is suspected, and for which an interpretation is performed as though the leads have in fact been interchanged. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: Suspicion of Limb Electrodes Reversal But Interpretation Assumes Reversal by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic recording in which an interchange of one or more limb lead electrodes is suspected, and for which an interpretation is performed as though the leads have in fact been interchanged. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Monomorphic Ventricular Tachycardia by ECG Finding

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Monomorphic Ventricular Tachycardia by ECG Finding
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of a ventricular tachycardia in which the QRS complexes have a uniform morphology. (CDISC)

Concepts.longName: Monomorphic Ventricular Tachycardia by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of a ventricular tachycardia in which the QRS complexes have a uniform morphology. (CDISC)

PermissibleValues.value: VOLTAGE CRITERIA SUGGESTING LEFT VENTRICULAR HYPERTROPHY, WITHOUT SECONDARY ECG FINDINGS
PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Voltage Criteria Suggesting Left Ventricular Hypertrophy, Without Secondary ECG Findings

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Voltage Criteria Suggesting Left Ventricular Hypertrophy, Without Secondary ECG Findings
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding of large QRS amplitudes that may indicate left ventricular hypertrophy, but is without any of the secondary findings that are typically seen with this diagnosis: left atrial enlargement, left axis deviation, or typical pattern of ST depression and T wave inversion.

Concepts.longName: Voltage Criteria Suggesting Left Ventricular Hypertrophy, Without Secondary ECG Findings
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of large QRS amplitudes that may indicate left ventricular hypertrophy, but is without any of the secondary findings that are typically seen with this diagnosis: left atrial enlargement, left axis deviation, or typical pattern of ST depression and T wave inversion.

PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Wolff-Parkinson-White Syndrome

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Wolff-Parkinson-White Syndrome
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A congenital electrical function abnormality in the heart. It is characterized by the presence of an accessory conductive pathway between the atria and the ventricles which causes the activation of the ventricles earlier than anticipated. Characteristic electrocardiographic findings are a short PR interval and a wide QRS complex with a delta wave.

Concepts.longName: Wolff-Parkinson-White Syndrome
Concepts.definition: A cardiac conduction disorder characterized by an electrocardiographic finding of ventricular pre-excitation, which is a short PR interval and a long QRS interval with a delta wave. Most individuals are asymptomatic; however they can experience periods of palpitations, shortness of breath or syncope during tachycardic episodes.

PermissibleValues.value: INSUFFICIENT NUMBER OF BEATS TO COMPLETELY EVALUATE ECG
PermissibleValues.valueDescription: Insufficient Number of Beats for Complete ECG Evaluation

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Insufficient Number of Beats for Complete ECG Evaluation
